<div class=3D"available-content"><div dir=3D"auto" class=3D"body markup"><p=
><span>I recently did a livestream with </span><div class=3D"profile-hover-=
card-target profileHoverCardTarget-PBxvGm"><a class=3D"mention-pnpTE1" href=
=3D"https://open.substack.com/users/11600151-michael-easter?utm_source=3Dme=
ntions" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener" data-attrs=3D"{&quot;name&quot;:=
&quot;Michael Easter&quot;,&quot;id&quot;:11600151,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;u=
ser&quot;,&quot;url&quot;:null,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack=
cdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fs=
ubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F263031a8-b7ad-4cc8-=
904e-432d4ec5af14_4320x3240.jpeg&quot;,&quot;uuid&quot;:&quot;cd4964aa-50c9=
-4397-8216-fc887d2edafc&quot;}" data-component-name=3D"MentionUser">Michael=
 Easter</a></div><span>, the former fitness director of Men=E2=80=99s Healt=
h magazine and the bestselling author of </span><em>The Comfort Crisis</em>=
<span> and </span><em>Scarcity Brain</em><span>. Michael also has a superb =
</span><a href=3D"https://www.twopct.com/" rel=3D"">Substack</a><span> whic=
h I recommend. </span></p><p>Some topics we discuss:</p><ul><li><p>Why stru=
ggle is essential=E2=80=94even if you have to manufacture it. Some people i=
nstinctively seek out hardship. If life isn=E2=80=99t hard enough, we find =
ways to make it harder.</p></li><li><p>Modern food is designed to defeat yo=
ur self-control. No one binges on apples or steak. But Doritos? Ice cream? =
These foods are chemically engineered to override your brain=E2=80=99s natu=
ral stop signals.</p></li><li><p>Dopamine isn=E2=80=99t the problem=E2=80=
=94how we get it is. The human brain evolved to reward effort, but in the m=
odern world, we=E2=80=99ve hacked the system. TikTok, junk food, and social=
 media offer dopamine shortcuts that leave us feeling worse in the long run=
.</p></li><li><p>Why maximizing makes sense for some things, but satisficin=
g is better for most others. You can=E2=80=99t perfect every detail of your=
 life, but there are a few areas=E2=80=94major projects, relationships, and=
 longer-term ambitions=E2=80=94where it pays to take your time.</p></li><li=
><p>Self-improvement messaging matters. Yes, everyone knows exercise is goo=
d for you. But knowing something and acting on it are two very different th=
ings. Constant reminders are what actually change behavior.</p></li><li><p>=
<span>Action beats inaction. Overthinking is often just a way of avoiding r=
isk. If you=E2=80=99re stuck, do something. Anything. That=E2=80=99s how mo=
mentum starts. Starting </span><em>badly</em><span> is still better than no=
t starting at all. Good results come from forward motion.</span></p></li><l=
i><p><span>Paralysis by analysis is killing your progress. Research shows t=
hat </span><a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/people-spend-too-much=
-time-on-decisions" rel=3D"">people waste time</a><span> agonizing over dec=
isions that won=E2=80=99t actually make much of a difference. If you=E2=80=
=99re debating between two good options, just pick one. When faced with a s=
et of options that are roughly equal, agonizing over them is wasted energy.=
</span></p></li><li><p>Most people fear criticism more than failure. The re=
al reason we hesitate? It=E2=80=99s not about getting it right=E2=80=94it=
=E2=80=99s about avoiding judgment.</p></li><li><p><span>How a viral tweet =
turned into a major idea. The origin story of </span><em><a href=3D"https:/=
/www.robkhenderson.com/p/status-symbols-and-the-struggle-for" rel=3D"">luxu=
ry beliefs</a></em><span>=E2=80=94how a Twitter thread became a series of e=
ssays, a chapter in my book, and a term embraced (and sometimes debated) ac=
ross the political spectrum.</span></p></li><li><p>Why social media makes o=
verconfidence a necessity. If you=E2=80=99re too cautious, no one notices. =
If you=E2=80=99re too bold, you get attacked. Striking the balance is a con=
stant challenge.</p></li><li><p>Can technology make us tougher? It=E2=80=99=
s just a tool, but how we use it determines whether it=E2=80=99s helping or=
 hurting our mental and physical well-being. How some innovations=E2=80=94l=
ike Pok=C3=A9mon Go=E2=80=94are tricking people into doing what=E2=80=99s g=
ood for them instead of what=E2=80=99s easy.</p></li><li><p>What it=E2=80=
=99s like to host meetups and gatherings for Substack readers</p></li><li><=
p>Reading books rewires your brain for deep thinking in a world of distract=
ions. Everything else is engineered to be quick, shallow, and forgettable=
=E2=80=94reading is one of the last refuges of real focus.</p></li></ul><di=
